	"nodes":[
		{"id":"3bb45b8281237e3f","type":"text","text":" ###### Normalization\n \n Database normalization is a database design principle for organizing data in an organized and consistent way.\n \n The main purpose of database normalization is to avoid complexities, eliminate duplicates, and organize data in a consistent way. In normalization, the data is divided into several tables linked together with relationships.\n \n All the types of database normalization are cumulative – meaning each one builds on top of those beneath it. So all the concepts in 1NF also carry over to 2NF, and so on.\n ------------------------------- \n \n ### 1NF\n ### - a single cell must not hold more than one value (atomicity)\n ##### - there must be a primary key for identification\n##### - no duplicated rows or columns\n##### - each column must have only one value for each row in the table\n\n-------\n### 2NF\n\t  avoiding redundancy\n\t\n\t\n- it’s already in 1NF\n- has no partial dependency. That is, all non-key attributes are fully dependent on a primary key.\n  All non-key columns must depend on the COMPLETE primary key — not just a part of it\n\n\nCON JOINED KEYS SHOULD NOT EXIT \n\nFOR EXAMPLE \nID: 1\nUID:HELLO\n\nWRONG ID :  1HELLO\n  \n  ![[Pasted image 20260414231740.png]]\n  \n  \n  ![[Pasted image 20260414231800.png]]|\n  \n  \n  -----\n  \n  ### 3NF\n  \n  NO Transitive Dependency\n  \n  **In Normalization (2NF & 3NF), we do this:**\n\n==We create a separate table for data that will be used **many times**. We store that data **only once** in its own table with a **Primary Key**. Then, in other tables, we just put the **Primary Key** (as a Foreign Key) to reference it.==\n\nThis way we avoid writing the same information again and again.\n  \n  \n  ![[Pasted image 20260414232336.png]]\n  ![[Pasted image 20260414232347.png]]\n  \n  \n  ----\n  \n  4NF\n  \n  **4NF removes Multi-Valued Dependency.**\n\nThat means: One record should not have **two or more independent lists** of values.\n\n|![[Pasted image 20260414233004.png]]\n\n\n![[Pasted image 20260414233018.png]]\n\n\n----\n\n**5NF** means the table has **no Join Dependency**.\n\nIt ensures that when you split a table into smaller tables and then join them back, you don’t get any **extra unwanted (spurious) rows**.\n\nSPLITING IN TO MULTIPLE TABLES USING PRIMARY  KEY TO LOOK THEM UP\n\n![[Pasted image 20260414233227.png]]\n\n\n![[Pasted image 20260414233240.png]]\n\n\n---\n\n\n6NF\n**6NF** is the highest normal form. It says: **Every table should have only one non-key column.**\n\nIn other words, each table becomes extremely small and “irreducible” — you cannot break it down any further.\n\nEACH TABLE ONLY HAS PRIMARY KEY ID AND ONE MORE COLUME NOTHING ELSE\n\n- **6NF**: Every non-key column must be in its own table.\n- Tables become very small and atomic.\n- Also called “Irreducible Normal Form”.\n  \n  \n\n![[Pasted image 20260414233616.png]]\n\n---\n\nde normailzation vs normalization\n\n### Easy Comparison:\n\n|Feature|Normalization|Denormalization|\n|---|---|---|\n|Redundancy|Removed (minimum)|Added intentionally|\n|Number of Tables|Many small tables|Fewer tables|\n|Query Speed (Read)|Slower (many JOINs)|Faster (less or no JOINs)|\n|Storage|Less storage|More storage|\n|Update / Insert|Easy & safe|Risky (update anomalies)|\n|Best For|OLTP systems (banking, etc.)|OLAP / Reporting / Data Warehouses|","x":400,"y":-240,"width":1000,"height":6920,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"4a611c03e6c8acc9","type":"text","text":"Dead letter queue config\n> \"I’d configure the main queue with a **dead letter exchange** and **dead letter routing key**. After 3 failed retries, I’d reject the message with requeue: false so it goes to the DLQ. On the DLQ side, I’d have a separate consumer or a monitoring alert that picks up these failed messages so we can investigate why they keep failing — maybe bad data, schema change, or a bug in the consumer.\"","x":3920,"y":-80,"width":653,"height":260},
		{"id":"607177d3d866fb0a","x":560,"y":-640,"width":1825,"height":50,"color":"5","type":"text","text":"Databases\n"},
		{"id":"c19c73ddf9d4504a","x":1560,"y":-200,"width":1472,"height":5440,"color":"5","type":"text","text":"MVCC Multiy Version Concurrency Control\n\n- PostgreSQL **never overwrites** a row.\n- UPDATE / DELETE → creates a **new version** of the row (old one stays).\n- Every transaction sees only the versions **visible to it** (via snapshot). → Readers & writers **never block** each other.\n  \n  \n  Every row version has **two hidden fields**:\n\n|Field|Name|Meaning|Who sets it|\n|---|---|---|---|\n|**xmin**|Creation TXID|Transaction that **created** this version|Automatically on INSERT/UPDATE|\n|**xmax**|Expiration TXID|Transaction that **deleted** this version (or NULL if still alive)|Automatically on UPDATE/DELETE|\n\n**Visibility rule (the only thing you need to remember):** A row version is **visible** to your transaction if:\n\n- xmin is committed **before** your snapshot started, **AND**\n- xmax is either **NULL** or committed **after** your snapshot started.\n\n\n```BEGIN;                  -- Transaction A starts\nINSERT/UPDATE ...       -- Creates NEW row version:\n                        --   xmin = A's TXID\n                        --   xmax = NULL\nCOMMIT;                 -- Now everyone can see it\n```\n\n**During the transaction (before COMMIT):**\n\n- Transaction A sees the **new** version.\n- Other transactions still see the **old** version.\n\n**After COMMIT:**\n\n- New version becomes visible to **all future** transactions.\n- Old version is marked with xmax = A’s TXID (so it becomes “dead”).\n  \n  ----\n  ### Quick Reference Card\n\n- **BEGIN** → new snapshot created.\n- **UPDATE** → new row version + old row gets xmax.\n- **SELECT** → sees only visible versions (no locks!).\n- **COMMIT** → makes your changes visible to everyone.\n- **ROLLBACK** → your new versions disappear (xmax never set).\n- **Long tx** = bad for bloat.\n- **Lost update?** → use SELECT ... FOR UPDATE or version column.\n\n**One-line mental model:**\n\n> “Every row has a birth certificate (xmin) and death certificate (xmax). Each transaction only looks at rows born before it and not yet dead.”\n  \n ---\n  ### VACUUM & Disk Space (Your Question)\n\n- Old versions stay on disk until **no transaction** can still see them.\n- **Autovacuum** (or manual VACUUM) removes dead tuples → frees space **inside** the table.\n- Disk space is **reused** for future inserts/updates (no immediate shrink).\n- Long-running transactions = more bloat (they block vacuum from cleaning old versions).\n  \n  \n  ```\n  VACUUM ANALYZE table_name;   -- clean + update stats\n  ```\n  \n  \n  \n  \n  \n-----\nTransaction Isolation Levels \n\nANOMALIES \n\n\n\n### 1. Dirty Read\n\n**Explanation**: Reading data that has been changed by another transaction **before it is committed**. You see data that might disappear if the other transaction rolls back.\n\n**Example**:\n\n- Transaction A: BEGIN; UPDATE accounts SET balance = 10000 WHERE id=1; (not committed yet)\n- Transaction B: SELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id=1; → sees **10000** (dirty read)\n- Transaction A: ROLLBACK;\n- Now the balance is actually still 500, but B already saw the wrong value.\n\n**Rare in Postgres** because even Read Uncommitted behaves like Read Committed.\n\n### 2. Non-Repeatable Read (Fuzzy Read)\n\n**Explanation**: You read the **same row twice** in one transaction and get **different values** because another transaction updated and committed it in between.\n\n**Example**:\n\nSQL\n\n```\nBEGIN;                              -- Your transaction\nSELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id=1;   -- Returns 1000\n\n-- Another user transfers money and commits\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = 1500 WHERE id=1;\n\nSELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id=1;   -- Returns 1500 ← Different value!\nCOMMIT;\n```\n\nThis is possible in **Read Committed**, but prevented in **Repeatable Read** and **Serializable**.\n\n\n### 3. Phantom Read\n\n**Explanation**: You run the **same query twice** and get **different number of rows** because another transaction inserted or deleted rows that match your WHERE condition.\n\n**Example**:\n\nSQL\n\n```\nBEGIN;\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 5;   -- Returns 3 orders\n\n-- Another transaction inserts a new order for customer 5 and commits\n\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 5;   -- Now returns 4 orders (phantom appeared!)\nCOMMIT;\n```\n\nThis is possible in **Read Committed**, but **prevented** in **Repeatable Read** and **Serializable** in PostgreSQL.\n\n\n\n### 4. Serialization Anomaly\n\n**Explanation**: The transactions run successfully, but the **final result** is impossible if the transactions had run one after another (serially). It's a more complex logical inconsistency.\n\n**Example** (Classic):\n\n- Transaction A: Move $100 from Account1 to Account2\n- Transaction B: Calculate total balance of Account1 + Account2 and report it\n\nBoth transactions succeed, but the reported total is wrong (as if money was created or lost). This can only be prevented by **Serializable** level.\n\n-------\n\n\n\n![[Screenshot 2026-04-16 at 13.32.35.png]]\n\n\n\n"}
